\section[Problem Statement]{Problem Statement}

The current system that's in place to serve patients from their homes is inefficient and costly. 
As it is based on the patients making phone calls directly to the call center to make an 
arrangement for their samples to be taken at home. Which introduces a need for more employees 
on the line, a bigger and more capable call-center, and perhaps even customer dissatisfaction 
in case the service was lousy or unavailable. This unfit and often confusing system will be 
renovated by the software to be developed in this project. Applications that will make the 
process far simpler, faster, and convenient for the patients. While lifting sizeable load 
off the call-center. Moreover, a real-time tracking system of the couriers will also greatly 
benefit the MedLabs business as a whole, by boosting the effectiveness of delivering the 
samples from and to the different branches.

\section[Related Work]{Related Work}

The Ground Positioning System (GPS) is owned and operated by the United States of America. 
It's a powerful system of more than 30 satellites orbiting the earth and constantly keeping 
a steady flow of signals being sent to ground stations scattered across the planet. 
This allows for the satellites' position to be known at all times. Using signals from at least 
4 of those satellites, a receiver can deduce its accurate position on the ground. 
This type of advanced and free to use technology should be used to better and improve existing 
and upcoming projects. This will be achieved in this project as we'll be incorporating a 
project our fellow students from PSUT's King Abdullah II School of Engineering have been 
working on. The project consists of a real-time tracking system that uses GPS to provide the 
most reliable positioning possible, regardless of whether the user has an active internet 
connection or not. This system will be built into each of the couriers' vehicles. 
And as long as a straight unobstructed line of sight is maintained between the vehicle and 
at least 4 satellites, the tracking will not be interrupted. 
